{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1781456531,"nonce":"90p61G1jP4jzJsP2lsI8tgS4NQ4=","title":"squealy's query builder cannot be used inside an `async fn` that returns","message":"`impl Future + Send` (i.e. RPITIT + `Send` in a trait method). The execution-query\ntrait impls — `ExecutableInsertQuery`, `InsertableTable`, `UpdateableTable`,\n`ExecutableUpdateQuery`, `DeleteSourceAst`, `ExecutableDeleteQuery` — are\nimplemented for a **specific** lifetime, not generically over the table/query\nlifetime. Producing a `Send` future requires them for **any** lifetime (HRTB),\nwhich the compiler reports as \"not general enough\" and \"lifetime bound not\nsatisfied\" (rust-lang/rust#100013).\n\nThis blocks using squealy behind any async trait whose methods are `-\u003e impl Future\n+ Send` — e.g. a backend trait consumed by a generic multithreaded async service.\n\n\n```rust\n// A backend trait whose methods must return Send futures (needed when a generic\n// `T: Store` is used across threads, e.g. an async-graphql resolver).\ntrait Store {\n    fn get(\u0026self, id: Uuid)\n        -\u003e impl std::future::Future\u003cOutput = Result\u003cOption\u003cRow\u003e, Error\u003e\u003e + Send;\n    fn remove(\u0026self, a: Uuid, b: Uuid)\n        -\u003e impl std::future::Future\u003cOutput = Result\u003c(), Error\u003e\u003e + Send;\n}\n\nimpl Store for PgStore {\n    async fn get(\u0026self, id: Uuid) -\u003e Result\u003cOption\u003cRow\u003e, Error\u003e {\n        let row = self.conn\n            .from::\u003cMyTable\u003e()\n            .where_(|t| t.id.equals(id))\n            .select(|(t,)| t)\n            .fetch_optional().await?;\n        Ok(row)\n    }\n\n    async fn remove(\u0026self, a: Uuid, b: Uuid) -\u003e Result\u003c(), Error\u003e {\n        self.conn\n            .from::\u003cMyTable\u003e()\n            .where_(|t| t.a.equals(a).and(t.b.equals(b)))\n            .delete().await?;\n        Ok(())\n    }\n}\n```\n\n\n```\nerror: implementation of `squealy::ExecutableInsertQuery` is not general enough\n   = note: `ExecutableInsertQuery\u003c'1, .., ()\u003e` would have to be implemented for the\n           type `PostgresInsert\u003c'0, schema::Organization\u003c'_\u003e, (), ..\u003e`, for any two\n           lifetimes `'0` and `'1`...\n   = note: ...but `ExecutableInsertQuery\u003c'2, .., ()\u003e` is actually implemented for\n           `PostgresInsert\u003c'2, schema::Organization\u003c'_\u003e, (), ..\u003e`, for some specific\n           lifetime `'2`\n\nerror: lifetime bound not satisfied\n   = note: this is a known limitation that will be removed in the future\n           (see issue #100013 \u003chttps://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/100013\u003e)\n```\n\nThe same shape appears for `UpdateableTable` / `ExecutableUpdateQuery` (on\n`update()`), `DeleteSourceAst` / `ExecutableDeleteQuery` (on `delete()`), and\n`InsertableTable` / `ExecutableInsertQuery` (on `insert()`).\n\n\nThe **identical method bodies compile with zero errors** as an *inherent* `async fn`\nimpl (`impl PgStore { async fn get(..) {..} }`), and fail **only** when the same\nbodies are a *trait* impl whose methods are `-\u003e impl Future + Send`. So the bodies\nand the builder usage are fine; the gap is that the execution-query trait impls\naren't general over the lifetime, so the resulting future can't be proven `Send`\nfor all lifetimes.\n\nTried and did **not** help:\n- Boxing the futures (`fn .. -\u003e impl Future + Send { Box::pin(async move { .. }) }`).\n- Pinning the table type to `'static` (`from::\u003cMyTable\u003c'static\u003e\u003e()`).\n\n\nThe execution-query trait impls should be general over the table/query lifetime\n(e.g. `for\u003c'a\u003e` / a lifetime parameter on the impl rather than a fixed one), so the\nbuilder composes with `async fn -\u003e impl Future + Send`. This is required to use\nsquealy from an async trait method that must return a `Send` future.\n\n\nBuilding the gitana catalog Postgres backend behind a `Catalog` trait whose methods\nare `-\u003e impl Future + Send` (required because the async-graphql resolvers are\ngeneric over the catalog backend and run on a multithreaded runtime). Every\ninsert/update/delete/select method is affected.","files":null}]}